const rawHTML = `
<div class="c">

<!-- Hero -->
<div class="hero">
  <div class="hero-k">Comparison &middot; GH Secretagogues &middot; GHRP vs GHRH</div>
  <h1>Ipamorelin vs Sermorelin: Comparing Growth Hormone Secretagogues</h1>
  <p class="sub">Two peptides that both trigger natural growth hormone release, but through completely different receptor systems. One mimics ghrelin. The other mimics GHRH. Here is how they compare on mechanism, dosing, side effects, and real-world results.</p>
  <div class="pills">
    <span class="pill">Ipamorelin &middot; GHRP</span>
    <span class="pill">Sermorelin &middot; GHRH Analog</span>
    <span class="pill">Body Composition &middot; Recovery</span>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- Stats -->
<div class="sr">
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c1">~711</div><div class="l">Ipamorelin<br>MW (Da)</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c2">~3,357</div><div class="l">Sermorelin<br>MW (Da)</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c3">2</div><div class="l">Distinct Receptor<br>Pathways</div></div>
  <div class="sb"><div class="v c4">GHS-R1a</div><div class="l">Ipamorelin<br>Primary Target</div></div>
</div>

<p>Ipamorelin and sermorelin sit at the center of the growth hormone peptide conversation, and for good reason. Both stimulate your pituitary gland to produce more GH naturally, which is a fundamentally different approach than injecting synthetic growth hormone directly.</p>

<p>But they get there through completely different doors. Ipamorelin knocks on the ghrelin receptor. Sermorelin knocks on the GHRH receptor. That distinction shapes everything from how fast they work to what side effects you might experience.</p>

<div class="d d-a">
  <div class="s">Important</div>
  <p>Both peptides require medical supervision. Consult a qualified healthcare provider before starting any <a href="/articles/what-are-peptides-beginners-guide">peptide protocol</a>. They can evaluate your health status and determine if GH secretagogues are appropriate for your situation.</p>
</div>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Ipamorelin Profile -->
<h2>Ipamorelin: The Selective GHRP</h2>

<p>Ipamorelin is a synthetic pentapeptide, just five amino acids long. It falls into the growth hormone-releasing peptide (GHRP) class, meaning it mimics ghrelin to trigger GH release from the pituitary.</p>

<p>What makes it stand out from other GHRPs is selectivity. Unlike <a href="/articles/hexarelin-complete-guide">hexarelin</a> or GHRP-6, ipamorelin does not significantly spike cortisol or prolactin. That targeted action is why it became the most popular entry-level GH peptide.</p>

<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Ipamorelin Profile</div>
  <h3>Key Characteristics</h3>
  <p><strong>Classification:</strong> Synthetic pentapeptide, growth hormone-releasing peptide (GHRP)</p>
  <p><strong>Molecular weight:</strong> Approximately 711 Da</p>
  <p><strong>Primary target:</strong> GHS-R1a (ghrelin receptor) on pituitary somatotrophs</p>
  <p><strong>GH release pattern:</strong> Rapid pulse peaking in 30-60 minutes</p>
  <p><strong>Regulatory status:</strong> Research compound, not FDA-approved for therapeutic use</p>
</div>

<p>The selectivity story is the real selling point. When researchers compared ipamorelin head-to-head with GHRP-2 and GHRP-6, ipamorelin produced equivalent GH output with minimal impact on other hormone axes. Your cortisol stays steady. Your prolactin stays steady. You just get the GH pulse.</p>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Sermorelin Profile -->
<h2>Sermorelin: The GHRH Analog</h2>

<p>Sermorelin is a 29-amino acid peptide that replicates the first 29 residues of your body's own growth hormone-releasing hormone. It was originally developed in the 1980s as a diagnostic tool for GH deficiency, and it actually held FDA approval for that purpose.</p>

<p>Its approach is more physiological than ipamorelin's. Instead of mimicking a hunger signal, sermorelin amplifies the same signaling pathway your hypothalamus already uses to tell the pituitary to release GH.</p>

<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Sermorelin Profile</div>
  <h3>Key Characteristics</h3>
  <p><strong>Classification:</strong> 29-amino acid synthetic GHRH analog</p>
  <p><strong>Molecular weight:</strong> Approximately 3,357 Da</p>
  <p><strong>Primary target:</strong> GHRH receptor on pituitary somatotrophs</p>
  <p><strong>GH release pattern:</strong> Gradual, sustained elevation over 1-2 hours</p>
  <p><strong>Regulatory status:</strong> Previously FDA-approved for diagnostic use (discontinued commercially)</p>
</div>

<p>The clinical pedigree matters here. <a href="/articles/sermorelin-growth-hormone-guide">Sermorelin</a> went through actual FDA trials in the 1990s. Researchers generated real safety and efficacy data in deficient populations, which gives it a more established evidence base than most research peptides.</p>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Mechanism Comparison -->
<h2>How They Work: Two Different Doors to the Same Room</h2>

<p>This is where the comparison gets interesting. Both peptides end up in the same place (more GH from your pituitary), but the pathways could not be more different.</p>

<div class="svg-box">
  <div class="st">GH Secretagogue Mechanism Comparison</div>
  <div class="ss">Two receptor pathways converging on pituitary GH release</div>
  <svg viewBox="0 0 700 220" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    <rect x="10" y="20" width="160" height="50" rx="8" fill="#E8EEF9" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="90" y="50" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="600" fill="#2956A6">Ipamorelin</text>
    <rect x="10" y="150" width="160" height="50" rx="8" fill="#E4F5EF" stroke="#187A62" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="90" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="600" fill="#187A62">Sermorelin</text>
    <rect x="230" y="20" width="160" height="50" rx="8" fill="#FFF7E5" stroke="#B48118" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="310" y="42" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#B48118">GHS-R1a</text>
    <text x="310" y="58" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#86869A">Ghrelin Receptor</text>
    <rect x="230" y="150" width="160" height="50" rx="8" fill="#FFF7E5" stroke="#B48118" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="310" y="172" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#B48118">GHRH-R</text>
    <text x="310" y="188" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10" fill="#86869A">GHRH Receptor</text>
    <rect x="460" y="75" width="180" height="70" rx="10" fill="#F3ECF8" stroke="#6E3B8A" stroke-width="1.5"/>
    <text x="550" y="100" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="600" fill="#6E3B8A">Pituitary Gland</text>
    <text x="550" y="118" text-anchor="middle" font-size="11" fill="#86869A">Somatotroph Cells</text>
    <text x="550" y="135" text-anchor="middle" font-size="13" font-weight="700" fill="#6E3B8A">GH Release</text>
    <line x1="170" y1="45" x2="230" y2="45" stroke="#2956A6" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
    <line x1="170" y1="175" x2="230" y2="175" stroke="#187A62" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
    <line x1="390" y1="45" x2="460" y2="95" stroke="#B48118" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
    <line x1="390" y1="175" x2="460" y2="125" stroke="#B48118" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr3)"/>
    <defs>
      <marker id="arr" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="6" refX="8" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L8,3 L0,6Z" fill="#2956A6"/></marker>
      <marker id="arr2" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="6" refX="8" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L8,3 L0,6Z" fill="#187A62"/></marker>
      <marker id="arr3" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="6" refX="8" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L8,3 L0,6Z" fill="#B48118"/></marker>
    </defs>
  </svg>
</div>

<h3>Ipamorelin's Pathway</h3>

<p>Ipamorelin binds the ghrelin receptor (GHS-R1a) on pituitary somatotroph cells. This is the same receptor that natural ghrelin activates when your stomach is empty. The binding triggers a rapid GH pulse that peaks within 30-60 minutes and clears within 2-3 hours.</p>

<p>Interestingly, ipamorelin produces almost no hunger signal despite hitting the ghrelin receptor. That is one of its unique properties compared to GHRP-6, which can make you ravenously hungry.</p>

<h3>Sermorelin's Pathway</h3>

<p>Sermorelin binds the GHRH receptor, the same target your hypothalamus uses for natural GH regulation. This produces a more gradual elevation that peaks around 60-120 minutes and can persist for 4-6 hours.</p>

<p>The sustained release pattern more closely mirrors your body's natural GH pulsatility. That is why some clinicians consider it the more "physiological" option of the two.</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Characteristic</th><th>Ipamorelin</th><th>Sermorelin</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Receptor target</strong></td><td>GHS-R1a (ghrelin)</td><td>GHRH-R</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Onset of action</strong></td><td><span class="g">15-30 min</span></td><td><span class="y">30-60 min</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Peak GH levels</strong></td><td>30-60 min</td><td>60-120 min</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Duration of effect</strong></td><td>2-3 hours</td><td>4-6 hours</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Hunger stimulation</strong></td><td><span class="g">Minimal</span></td><td><span class="y">Moderate</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Cortisol impact</strong></td><td><span class="g">Negligible</span></td><td><span class="g">Minimal</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Prolactin impact</strong></td><td><span class="g">Negligible</span></td><td><span class="g">Minimal</span></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Side Effects -->
<h2>Side Effect Profiles</h2>

<p>Both peptides are generally well-tolerated, which is part of their appeal compared to direct GH injections. But they do differ in their side effect signatures.</p>

<p>Ipamorelin's selectivity gives it a cleaner profile overall. Sermorelin's broader mechanism means slightly more potential for off-target effects, though most are mild and transient.</p>

<table class="tbl">
  <thead><tr><th>Side Effect</th><th>Ipamorelin</th><th>Sermorelin</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Injection site reactions</strong></td><td><span class="y">Common</span></td><td><span class="y">Common</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Headache</strong></td><td><span class="y">Occasional</span></td><td><span class="y">Occasional</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Flushing or warmth</strong></td><td><span class="y">Occasional</span></td><td><span class="y">Occasional</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Increased hunger</strong></td><td><span class="g">Rare</span></td><td><span class="y">Common</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Joint discomfort</strong></td><td><span class="g">Rare</span></td><td><span class="y">Occasional</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Water retention</strong></td><td><span class="g">Minimal</span></td><td><span class="y">Moderate</span></td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Carpal tunnel symptoms</strong></td><td><span class="g">Very rare</span></td><td><span class="g">Rare</span></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="d d-r">
  <div class="s">Safety Note</div>
  <p>Certain conditions may contraindicate GH secretagogue use, including active cancer, uncontrolled diabetes, and pituitary disorders. Always discuss your full medical history with a provider. Review our <a href="/articles/peptide-side-effects-what-to-know">peptide side effects guide</a> for broader context.</p>
</div>

<p>Most side effects resolve within the first few weeks as the body adjusts. Proper <a href="/articles/how-to-inject-peptides-subcutaneously">injection technique</a> and rotating sites minimizes local reactions significantly.</p>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Dosing -->
<h2>Dosing Protocols</h2>

<p>Dosing differs substantially between these two peptides, both in amount and in timing strategy. This reflects their different pharmacokinetics and receptor dynamics.</p>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="cd cb">
    <div class="tg">Ipamorelin Dosing</div>
    <h3>Typical Protocol</h3>
    <p><strong>Daily dose:</strong> 200-300 mcg</p>
    <p><strong>Frequency:</strong> 1-2 times daily</p>
    <p><strong>Timing:</strong> Bedtime and/or post-exercise</p>
    <p><strong>Cycle length:</strong> 8-12 weeks</p>
    <p><strong>Break period:</strong> 4-6 weeks between cycles</p>
  </div>
  <div class="cd ct">
    <div class="tg">Sermorelin Dosing</div>
    <h3>Typical Protocol</h3>
    <p><strong>Daily dose:</strong> 100-300 mcg</p>
    <p><strong>Frequency:</strong> Once daily</p>
    <p><strong>Timing:</strong> Before bedtime (aligns with natural GH pulse)</p>
    <p><strong>Cycle length:</strong> 3-6 months</p>
    <p><strong>Break period:</strong> 1-2 months between cycles</p>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Ipamorelin's shorter action window makes split dosing practical. Many users take one dose post-workout to support recovery, then a second dose at bedtime to sync with the natural nocturnal GH surge.</p>

<p>Sermorelin's sustained release makes once-daily dosing sufficient for most people. Bedtime administration capitalizes on your body's existing GH rhythm, which peaks during deep sleep.</p>

<div class="d d-t">
  <div class="s">Dosing Principle</div>
  <p>More is not better with GH peptides. Excessive doses can desensitize receptors over time, actually reducing your response. Start low, titrate slowly, and follow your provider's recommendations. See our <a href="/articles/peptide-cycling-guide">cycling guide</a> for more on preventing receptor downregulation.</p>
</div>

<p>Both peptides require <a href="/articles/how-to-reconstitute-peptides">reconstitution</a> before use. Use bacteriostatic water, inject slowly along the vial wall, and <a href="/articles/how-to-store-peptides">store reconstituted vials</a> at 36-46 degrees F. Use within 30 days of mixing.</p>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- Research -->
<h2>What the Research Actually Shows</h2>

<p>Neither peptide has the massive clinical trial portfolio of something like <a href="/articles/semaglutide-weight-loss-guide">semaglutide</a>. But both have meaningful research behind them, with sermorelin holding the edge due to its FDA trial history.</p>

<h3>Ipamorelin Research Highlights</h3>

<p>A 12-week study in healthy older adults showed approximately 20% increases in IGF-1 levels with ipamorelin administration. Participants reported improvements in body composition without significant adverse effects.</p>

<p>Animal studies suggest ipamorelin may support collagen synthesis, which could benefit <a href="/articles/best-peptides-for-joint-health">joint health</a> and skin integrity. Human data on these secondary benefits remains preliminary.</p>

<h3>Sermorelin Research Highlights</h3>

<p>Clinical data from sermorelin's FDA approval phase demonstrated clear efficacy in GH-deficient patients. Subjects achieved normalized growth hormone levels with consistent dosing over 6-12 month periods.</p>

<p>Multiple studies indicate sermorelin may enhance <a href="/articles/best-peptides-for-sleep">sleep quality</a>, particularly deep-wave sleep duration. This aligns with its bedtime dosing recommendation and could be a meaningful secondary benefit for recovery-focused users.</p>

